.Dd June 26, 2026
.Dt SD 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm sd
.Nd Secure-Enclave-backed SSH key, agent, and loader
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Cm ssh-keygen
.Op Fl f Ar keyfile
.Op Fl C Ar comment
.Op Fl t Cm ecdsa
.Op Fl y
.Nm
.Cm ssh-agent
.Op Fl a Ar socket
.Op Fl s | Fl c
.Op Fl d | Fl k
.Op Ar provider ...
.Nm
.Cm ssh-add
.Op Fl a Ar socket
.Oo Fl d | Fl D | Fl l | Fl L Oc
.Op Ar keyfile ...
.Nm
.Cm install
.Op Fl a Ar socket
.Nm
.Cm uninstall
.Nm
.Cm doctor
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
keeps an SSH authentication key in the Secure Enclave and serves it to stock
OpenSSH over the ssh-agent protocol.
The private key is generated inside the Secure Enclave and never leaves it;
Touch ID is required for every signature.
The commands mirror the OpenSSH tools they imitate.
.Ss sd ssh-keygen
Create a Secure-Enclave P-256 key: an opaque handle file plus a standard
.Pa .pub
public-key line.
.Bl -tag -width "-C comment"
.It Fl f Ar keyfile
Output keyfile (default
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod ) .
.It Fl C Ar comment
Comment for the public-key line (default
.Ar user@host ) .
.It Fl t Cm ecdsa
Key type; only
.Cm ecdsa
is accepted (the Secure Enclave is P-256 only).
.It Fl y
Read a handle file and print its public-key line.
.El
.Ss sd ssh-agent
Run the agent on a unix socket.
With no options it ensures an agent is running (reusing one if present) and
prints shell commands to set
.Ev SSH_AUTH_SOCK :
.Dl eval \&"$(sd ssh-agent)\&"
.Pp
The default key
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod
is served automatically; no
.Cm sd ssh-add
is needed.
Drop it for the session with
.Fl d
or
.Fl D .
.Bl -tag -width "-a socket"
.It Fl a Ar socket
Socket path (default
.Pa ~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock ) .
.It Fl s | Fl c
Force Bourne-shell (sh) or C-shell (csh) env output (default: detect from
.Ev SHELL ) .
.It Fl d
Foreground mode: bind and serve, do not fork (debugging / LaunchAgent).
.It Fl k
Kill the agent running on the socket.
.El
.Pp
To run the agent automatically at login, see
.Cm sd install
below.
.Ss sd ssh-add
Load, unload, or list keys.
With no arguments, loads the default key
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod .
.Bl -tag -width "-a socket"
.It Fl a Ar socket
Agent socket (default
.Ev SSH_AUTH_SOCK ,
else
.Pa ~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock ) .
.It Fl d , Fl e
Unload the given key(s).
.It Fl D
Unload all keys.
.It Fl l , Fl L
List loaded keys as fingerprints
.Pq Fl l
or full public keys
.Pq Fl L .
.El
.Ss sd install
Set up everything in one step: if the default key
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod
does not exist, offer to create it, then install a per-user LaunchAgent
that runs
.Cm sd ssh-agent
on a fixed socket at login (restarting it if it exits).
The agent serves
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod
automatically, so no
.Cm sd ssh-add
is required.
Finally it prints the
.Ic echo
and
.Ic exec
commands to point your shell at the agent.
This is the recommended setup after installing
.Nm ;
it never edits your shell files itself.
.Bl -tag -width "-a socket"
.It Fl a Ar socket
Socket path (default
.Pa ~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock ) .
.El
.Pp
To use
.Nm
for only some hosts and keep your existing agent for the rest, skip the
.Ev SSH_AUTH_SOCK
line and instead set
.Cm IdentityAgent ~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock
per-host in
.Xr ssh_config 5 .
.Ss sd uninstall
Remove the LaunchAgent installed by
.Cm sd install .
.Ss sd doctor
Check the health of your setup and print actionable hints; read-only, it
inspects but never changes anything.
It reports whether the Secure Enclave is available, the default key
.Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod
exists, the login agent is installed and loaded, the agent socket is live and
holds your key, and whether
.Ev SSH_AUTH_SOCK
is set in the current shell and exported from your shell startup file.
Exits non-zero if any check fails.
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width SSH_AUTH_SOCK
.It Ev SSH_AUTH_SOCK
Default agent socket for
.Cm ssh-add .
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width "~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock"
.It Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod
Default key handle.
.It Pa ~/.ssh/id_sod.pub
Default public key.
.It Pa ~/.ssh/sod-agent.sock
Default agent socket.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
Set it up to run at login (recommended), then follow the printed instructions
and load the key:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
sd ssh-keygen
sd install
sd ssh-add
.Ed
.Pp
Or run a throwaway agent in the current shell, load a key, and connect:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
sd ssh-keygen -f ~/.ssh/id_sod
eval \&"$(sd ssh-agent)\&"
sd ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_sod
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_sod user@host
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr ssh 1 ,
.Xr ssh-add 1 ,
.Xr ssh-agent 1 ,
.Xr ssh-keygen 1
.Sh AUTHORS
.An Botanica Software Labs
.Sh CAVEATS
macOS only.
The Secure Enclave requires Apple Silicon or a T2 chip.
.Pp
The agent does not enforce
.Xr ssh-add 1
key constraints \(em destination
.Pq Fl h ,
lifetime
.Pq Fl t ,
or confirm
.Pq Fl c .
A constrained add is
.Em refused
rather than honored as an unconstrained one, so a constraint that would not be
enforced never appears to succeed.
Touch ID gates every signature regardless.
